INSERT INTO news_stories (id, record_id, url, body_text, ai_summary) VALUES ('bd6d1cce-142f-4149-9067-f870146ce7ba', '1f69dd83-fb58-44f4-8b6c-4120d620d963', 'https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/assault-rifle-used-in-shooting-at-deli/article18269064/', 'Skip to main contentAdChoicesCanadaWorldBusinessInvestingWatchlistPersonal FinanceOpinionPoliticsSportsLifeArtsDriveReal EstatePodcastsAssault rifle used in shooting at deliJONATHAN FOWLIEPublished July 29, 2004This article was published more than 18 years ago. Some information may no longer be current.ShareLouise Russo, the woman badly wounded by an errant bullet while standing in a North York sandwich shop, was shot with a high-powered assault rifle normally used in military operations and rarely seen on the streets, Detective Brian Bott said yesterday.Displaying the sinister-looking semi-automatic weapon at a press conference yesterday, Det. Bott said Toronto police have determined that at least three people in a minivan pulled in front of California Sandwiches on April 21 and opened fire, striking Ms. Russo in the back and paralyzing her from the waist down.Det. Bott said he believes the drive-by shooting was not random, but made clear he thinks it highly unlikely that Ms. Russo, a 45-year-old mother of three teenagers, was the intended target.The head of a seven-member task force looking into the three-month-old case said, however, that he is unable to offer any plausible motive for the crime.&#34;I think there is a reason for it,&#34; Det. Bott said, adding, &#34;I don&#39;t know yet what that reason is.&#34;None of the other people in or around the shop at the time appeared to have reason to be targets of a drive-by shooting, he said.Det. Bott did say, however, that he is &#34;happy&#34; with the progress made by his task force so far, and that he is &#34;much more confident now than I was on April 26, when the task force was formed, that we will come to a successful conclusion.&#34;From her wheelchair yesterday, Ms. Russo told reporters gathered at police headquarters that every day since she was shot has been a &#34;struggle&#34; and that she still is feeling &#34;very weak.&#34;&#34;This has totally changed my life and the life of my family,&#34; she said, flanked by husband Sam, sister Rose and other members of her family.&#34;I could have easily been your mother, your wife, your sister or your daughter,&#34; she said, appealing to the public, urging anyone with information about the shooters or the case to come forward.&#34;If you know anything, please call,&#34; she added, tears flowing from her eyes.Ms. Russo was shot on the evening of April 21 when she went to buy a veal sandwich as a treat for 15-year-old Krista, her youngest daughter who was waiting outside the store in a van.While Ms. Russo was buying the sandwich, as many as 20 bullets came flying through the window of the store, one of which grazed her head. Another bullet went into her back, shattering vertebrae and breaking a rib.Still obviously distraught yesterday, Ms. Russo did not get into the details of how her life has changed, except to say she has been constantly enduring extreme amounts of &#34;physical emotional and mental anguish . . . each and every day.&#34;In previous interviews, she has said the incident has been a huge burden, not only because of the challenges of her own injuries, but because she has a 16-year-old daughter with a rare genetic disease who needs round-the-clock care.Det. Bott said police had recovered a Colt AR-15 assault rifle not long after the incident at a location near the scene, and that it has now been conclusively linked to the shooting. After tracing the serial number, police determined that the weapon had been stolen in a break and enter within the province 11 years ago, he said.He added that while the weapon can be legally bought by consumers, it is mostly used for target practice. It is also the type of rifle used by some militaries and by Toronto&#39;s Emergency Task Force.&#34;We very rarely run into those weapons [on the street]&#34; he said. &#34;I personally have never seen one before used in an incident.&#34;Det. Bott added that a second weapon, likely a handgun, was also used in the shooting but has yet to be recovered. Police believe two people fired their weapons out the open sliding door of a van that pulled up to the store just before the shooting.Follow us on Twitter: @globeandmailOpens in a new windowReport an errorEditorial code of conductTerms &amp; ConditionsCommunity GuidelinesPrivacy PolicyDisclaimerSkip footer navigationSubscribeDigital + Home DeliveryDigital AccessGlobe2GoThe New York TimesGlobe Email NewslettersGift SubscriptionBusiness servicesAdvertise with UsGroup SubscriptionsGlobe CampusContent LicensingDataStoreReport On Business Top 1000Globe Event CentreSophi.ioContact usAddress and Phone NumberPublic EditorStaffStaff PGP DirectorySecureDropSubmit an articleReader servicesMy globeandmail.com AccountTechnical Support &amp; FAQsManage my home deliveryManage my privacy preferencesManage my advertising preferencesMember BenefitsAbout usCompany informationWork at The GlobeAccessibilityEditorial Code of ConductSustainabilityLicensing &amp; PermissionsElection Advertising RegistrySubscribeDigital + Home DeliveryDigital AccessGlobe2GoThe New York TimesGlobe Email NewslettersGift SubscriptionBusiness servicesAdvertise with UsGroup SubscriptionsGlobe CampusContent LicensingDataStoreReport On Business Top 1000Globe Event CentreSophi.ioContact usAddress and Phone NumberPublic EditorStaffStaff PGP DirectorySecureDropSubmit an articleReader servicesMy globeandmail.com AccountTechnical Support &amp; FAQsManage my home deliveryManage my privacy preferencesManage my advertising preferencesMember BenefitsAbout usCompany informationWork at The GlobeAccessibilityEditorial Code of ConductSustainabilityLicensing &amp; PermissionsElection Advertising RegistryReturn to start of footer navigation¬© Copyright 20